Just to save the time to
take to the negative root.

01:07:10.660 --> 01:07:16.180 align:middle line:84%
And then p3 p4 to be
the positive root.

01:07:16.180 --> 01:07:21.760 align:middle line:90%


01:07:21.760 --> 01:07:24.250 align:middle line:84%
And then you put
the t here, then

01:07:24.250 --> 01:07:30.610 align:middle line:84%
you truncate your
external propagator.

01:07:30.610 --> 01:07:33.580 align:middle line:84%
Then you truncate your
external propagator.

01:07:33.580 --> 01:07:37.520 align:middle line:84%
What this means, let's look at
the leading order contribution

01:07:37.520 --> 01:07:38.020 align:middle line:90%
to this.

01:07:38.020 --> 01:07:41.925 align:middle line:90%


01:07:41.925 --> 01:07:43.550 align:middle line:84%
The leading order
contribution to that,

01:07:43.550 --> 01:07:44.967 align:middle line:84%
we already have
the diagram there.

01:07:44.967 --> 01:07:52.450 align:middle line:90%


01:07:52.450 --> 01:07:56.960 align:middle line:84%
The leading order,
in the free theory,

01:07:56.960 --> 01:07:59.870 align:middle line:84%
those processes don't
contribute because those things,

01:07:59.870 --> 01:08:01.370 align:middle line:90%
there's no interaction here.

01:08:01.370 --> 01:08:03.600 align:middle line:90%
Particle just propagates.

01:08:03.600 --> 01:08:07.070 align:middle line:84%
So the lowest
diagram is this one.

01:08:07.070 --> 01:08:09.560 align:middle line:84%
The lowest diagram is
this one, so we just

01:08:09.560 --> 01:08:12.350 align:middle line:84%
consider that diagram, so
that's just leading order

01:08:12.350 --> 01:08:13.415 align:middle line:90%
given by that diagram.

01:08:13.415 --> 01:08:18.990 align:middle line:90%


01:08:18.990 --> 01:08:28.939 align:middle line:84%
Then you have minus p1
minus p2 and then p3 and p4.

01:08:28.939 --> 01:08:32.609 align:middle line:90%


01:08:32.609 --> 01:08:38.279 align:middle line:84%
Now according to our Feynman
rule, this vertex just

01:08:38.279 --> 01:08:42.390 align:middle line:84%
gives you a factor
of minus i lambda.

01:08:42.390 --> 01:08:45.870 align:middle line:84%
So if we want to calculate
this Green function,

01:08:45.870 --> 01:08:50.490 align:middle line:84%
then we need to include
all these four propagators.

01:08:50.490 --> 01:08:53.640 align:middle line:84%
But here it tells
us to truncate,

01:08:53.640 --> 01:08:56.810 align:middle line:84%
but all the propagators
here are external,

01:08:56.810 --> 01:08:58.439 align:middle line:90%
so we don't include them.

01:08:58.439 --> 01:09:00.770 align:middle line:84%
So the answer here is
simple-- just minus i lambda.

01:09:00.770 --> 01:09:03.460 align:middle line:90%


01:09:03.460 --> 01:09:06.040 align:middle line:84%
The leading order contribution
to these 4 particles

01:09:06.040 --> 01:09:07.540 align:middle line:84%
scattering is just
minus i lambda.

01:09:07.540 --> 01:09:10.979 align:middle line:90%


01:09:10.979 --> 01:09:17.200 align:middle line:84%
And then you have all the
lambda squared contributions.

01:09:17.200 --> 01:09:17.830 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:09:17.830 --> 01:09:19.622 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why didn't
we consider the other,

01:09:19.622 --> 01:09:22.000 align:middle line:84%
the one where one
is just propagating

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:23.314 align:middle line:90%
and the other has a loop?

01:09:23.314 --> 01:09:28.460 align:middle line:90%


01:09:28.460 --> 01:09:31.550 align:middle line:84%
HONG LIU: I'm going
to mention that good.

01:09:31.550 --> 01:09:32.810 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

01:09:32.810 --> 01:09:35.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to mention that.

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:37.532 align:middle line:84%
Again, that one does not
correspond to the scattering.

01:09:37.532 --> 01:09:38.990 align:middle line:84%
Essentially it's
just corresponding

01:09:38.990 --> 01:09:42.200 align:middle line:84%
to one particle
propagated because there's

01:09:42.200 --> 01:09:45.680 align:middle line:84%
no interaction
between the particles.

01:09:45.680 --> 01:09:46.819 align:middle line:90%
They factorize.

01:09:46.819 --> 01:09:50.510 align:middle line:90%


01:09:50.510 --> 01:09:53.903 align:middle line:84%
This one involves the two
particles then, there's

01:09:53.903 --> 01:09:55.820 align:middle line:84%
an interaction, you go
to two other particles.

01:09:55.820 --> 01:10:00.000 align:middle line:84%
Here just one particle straight
goes to the other particle,

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:02.870 align:middle line:84%
so this particle by definition
has to be the same as this one,

01:10:02.870 --> 01:10:07.220 align:middle line:84%
this has to be the same,
so there's no scattering.

01:10:07.220 --> 01:10:12.700 align:middle line:84%
I will mention this point
separately a little bit later.

01:10:12.700 --> 01:10:17.850 align:middle line:84%
Another possibility
if we want to consider

01:10:17.850 --> 01:10:28.580 align:middle line:84%
the decay of a particle
into three other particles.

01:10:28.580 --> 01:10:32.510 align:middle line:90%


01:10:32.510 --> 01:10:36.320 align:middle line:84%
The decay of a particle
into three other particles.

01:10:36.320 --> 01:10:41.090 align:middle line:84%
In this case then,
again, we take G4,

01:10:41.090 --> 01:10:46.670 align:middle line:84%
so now we take minus
p1, and then p2, p3, p4,

01:10:46.670 --> 01:10:49.670 align:middle line:90%
and now we take p1, p4.

01:10:49.670 --> 01:10:56.400 align:middle line:84%
Now we take p1 goes to minus
root, p1 0 is the minus omega,

01:10:56.400 --> 01:11:03.620 align:middle line:84%
and then p3, 2, 3, 4 take
it to be the positive root.

01:11:03.620 --> 01:11:06.110 align:middle line:84%
And then that's corresponding
to this process.

01:11:06.110 --> 01:11:12.120 align:middle line:84%
And again, the leading term, the
nontrivial term is just this.

01:11:12.120 --> 01:11:16.650 align:middle line:84%
The leading nontrivial term is
this, so now this is minus p1,

01:11:16.650 --> 01:11:22.320 align:middle line:90%
so now this is p2, p3, p4.

01:11:22.320 --> 01:11:25.988 align:middle line:84%
Again, the leading order,
this is just minus i lambda

01:11:25.988 --> 01:11:28.155 align:middle line:84%
because you don't need to
include the external legs.

01:11:28.155 --> 01:11:31.890 align:middle line:90%


01:11:31.890 --> 01:11:34.110 align:middle line:84%
This goes on to a
single particle decay

01:11:34.110 --> 01:11:35.550 align:middle line:90%
into three other particles.

01:11:35.550 --> 01:11:51.150 align:middle line:90%


01:11:51.150 --> 01:11:52.830 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the phi
4 theory, there's

01:11:52.830 --> 01:11:58.050 align:middle line:84%
no conservation law or anything
for preventing this, right?

01:11:58.050 --> 01:11:58.830 align:middle line:90%
HONG LIU: No, no.

01:11:58.830 --> 01:12:02.280 align:middle line:90%


01:12:02.280 --> 01:12:03.900 align:middle line:90%
So now let me make some remarks.

01:12:03.900 --> 01:12:33.290 align:middle line:90%


01:12:33.290 --> 01:12:33.800 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

01:12:33.800 --> 01:12:36.050 align:middle line:84%
I erased this, but
yeah, I'm fine.

01:12:36.050 --> 01:12:48.610 align:middle line:90%


01:12:48.610 --> 01:12:49.510 align:middle line:90%
So the remarks.

01:12:49.510 --> 01:12:59.460 align:middle line:90%


01:12:59.460 --> 01:13:01.860 align:middle line:84%
You already asked,
when we calculate

01:13:01.860 --> 01:13:03.930 align:middle line:84%
this to the leading
order, we only

01:13:03.930 --> 01:13:05.595 align:middle line:90%
included the connected diagrams.

01:13:05.595 --> 01:13:09.230 align:middle line:90%


01:13:09.230 --> 01:13:20.620 align:middle line:84%
The disconnected diagrams
in general factorize.

01:13:20.620 --> 01:13:25.030 align:middle line:84%
It means that when you
have disconnected diagram,

01:13:25.030 --> 01:13:33.920 align:middle line:84%
it means that your process
factorizes into subscattering

01:13:33.920 --> 01:13:43.385 align:middle line:90%
process of lower orders.

01:13:43.385 --> 01:13:53.990 align:middle line:90%


01:13:53.990 --> 01:13:58.220 align:middle line:84%
As we were doing here, there's
one other diagram which

01:13:58.220 --> 01:14:01.310 align:middle line:90%
corresponds to just this one.

01:14:01.310 --> 01:14:04.520 align:middle line:90%


01:14:04.520 --> 01:14:06.020 align:middle line:84%
Just corresponding
to this, you have

01:14:06.020 --> 01:14:14.750 align:middle line:90%
p1 minus p1, minus p2, p3, p4.

01:14:14.750 --> 01:14:17.900 align:middle line:84%
You can also have a
diagram like this.

01:14:17.900 --> 01:14:19.400 align:middle line:84%
But in this case,
just corresponding

01:14:19.400 --> 01:14:23.690 align:middle line:84%
to p1 separately go to p3
and p2 separately goes to p4,

01:14:23.690 --> 01:14:26.690 align:middle line:90%
so nothing really happens.

01:14:26.690 --> 01:14:32.440 align:middle line:84%
So in general, you have
m particle scattering.

01:14:32.440 --> 01:14:35.260 align:middle line:90%
You have m particle scattering.

01:14:35.260 --> 01:14:39.310 align:middle line:84%
So with some number
of initial particles

01:14:39.310 --> 01:14:43.960 align:middle line:84%
and some number of
final particles.

01:14:43.960 --> 01:14:47.920 align:middle line:84%
When you have a
disconnected diagram,

01:14:47.920 --> 01:14:51.170 align:middle line:84%
it means that you have
a situation like this.

01:14:51.170 --> 01:14:55.120 align:middle line:84%
You have one diagram with
some subset of particles

01:14:55.120 --> 01:14:58.780 align:middle line:84%
go to some subset of particles,
and with a lot of diagrams

01:14:58.780 --> 01:15:01.225 align:middle line:84%
some set of particles,
some set of particles.

01:15:01.225 --> 01:15:03.940 align:middle line:90%


01:15:03.940 --> 01:15:05.890 align:middle line:84%
This is a three to
three scattering,

01:15:05.890 --> 01:15:08.560 align:middle line:84%
and then essentially this
factorizes into two to two

01:15:08.560 --> 01:15:10.360 align:middle line:84%
scattering, and then
one particle just

01:15:10.360 --> 01:15:12.670 align:middle line:90%
goes to another particle.

01:15:12.670 --> 01:15:14.620 align:middle line:84%
This can already be
understood in terms

01:15:14.620 --> 01:15:15.670 align:middle line:90%
of lower order process.

01:15:15.670 --> 01:15:20.590 align:middle line:90%


01:15:20.590 --> 01:15:21.685 align:middle line:90%
We don't include them.

01:15:21.685 --> 01:15:24.162 align:middle line:90%


01:15:24.162 --> 01:15:25.870 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, they are
already understood.

01:15:25.870 --> 01:15:28.970 align:middle line:90%


01:15:28.970 --> 01:15:31.280 align:middle line:84%
When we define the
scattering amplitude,

01:15:31.280 --> 01:15:32.330 align:middle line:90%
we don't include them.

01:15:32.330 --> 01:15:37.060 align:middle line:90%


01:15:37.060 --> 01:15:56.280 align:middle line:84%
We are only interested
in process involving

01:15:56.280 --> 01:15:57.960 align:middle line:90%
all participating particles.

01:15:57.960 --> 01:16:09.800 align:middle line:90%


01:16:09.800 --> 01:16:11.525 align:middle line:84%
We are actually
running out of time.

01:16:11.525 --> 01:16:19.150 align:middle line:90%


01:16:19.150 --> 01:16:20.170 align:middle line:90%
This is first remark.

01:16:20.170 --> 01:16:23.630 align:middle line:90%


01:16:23.630 --> 01:16:24.380 align:middle line:90%
Second remark.

01:16:24.380 --> 01:16:29.120 align:middle line:90%


01:16:29.120 --> 01:16:33.360 align:middle line:84%
Since we truncate all
the external legs,

01:16:33.360 --> 01:16:36.690 align:middle line:84%
we truncate all the
external propagators.

01:16:36.690 --> 01:16:43.750 align:middle line:84%
This kind of diagram,
you have a loop on one

01:16:43.750 --> 01:16:47.350 align:middle line:84%
of the external
propagators, so this diagram

01:16:47.350 --> 01:16:48.260 align:middle line:90%
doesn't contribute.

01:16:48.260 --> 01:16:54.340 align:middle line:90%


01:16:54.340 --> 01:16:59.020 align:middle line:84%
Because this one, after you have
truncated the external legs,

01:16:59.020 --> 01:17:02.320 align:middle line:84%
it's no different
from this one, it's

01:17:02.320 --> 01:17:05.620 align:middle line:84%
no different from that
one, so you don't have

01:17:05.620 --> 01:17:08.380 align:middle line:90%
to count this one separately.

01:17:08.380 --> 01:17:09.820 align:middle line:84%
So this one is
just corresponding

01:17:09.820 --> 01:17:15.160 align:middle line:84%
to when the particle propagates
to infinity somehow there's

01:17:15.160 --> 01:17:18.910 align:middle line:84%
some other process to happen
to this particular particle.

01:17:18.910 --> 01:17:22.360 align:middle line:84%
When you truncate the external
legs, they don't include them.

01:17:22.360 --> 01:17:28.920 align:middle line:90%


01:17:28.920 --> 01:17:32.580 align:middle line:84%
So that means,
with these two, it

01:17:32.580 --> 01:17:34.650 align:middle line:84%
means that the
scattering amplitude--

01:17:34.650 --> 01:17:42.570 align:middle line:90%


01:17:42.570 --> 01:17:48.460 align:middle line:84%
Essentially can forget anything
happening to the external legs.

01:17:48.460 --> 01:17:54.590 align:middle line:90%


01:17:54.590 --> 01:17:57.230 align:middle line:84%
You can have complicated
things happen external legs,

01:17:57.230 --> 01:17:58.210 align:middle line:90%
but they don't matter.

01:17:58.210 --> 01:18:02.700 align:middle line:90%


01:18:02.700 --> 01:18:09.000 align:middle line:84%
To summarize, the
scattering amplitude,

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:13.740 align:middle line:84%
when you compute the scattering
amplitude, you just sum over--

01:18:13.740 --> 01:18:17.030 align:middle line:90%


01:18:17.030 --> 01:18:20.990 align:middle line:84%
following this definition--
you sum over all truncated.

01:18:20.990 --> 01:18:24.395 align:middle line:84%
It means that you truncate
all the external legs.

01:18:24.395 --> 01:18:27.580 align:middle line:90%


01:18:27.580 --> 01:18:34.555 align:middle line:84%
Connected because we want
all particles to participate.

01:18:34.555 --> 01:18:36.640 align:middle line:84%
And then the external
particle on-shell.

01:18:36.640 --> 01:18:44.240 align:middle line:90%


01:18:44.240 --> 01:18:46.820 align:middle line:84%
This is a
simplification compared

01:18:46.820 --> 01:18:49.687 align:middle line:84%
to calculating the general
correlation functions.

01:18:49.687 --> 01:18:52.220 align:middle line:90%


01:18:52.220 --> 01:18:54.980 align:middle line:84%
I have two other remarks to
make, but we don't have time.

01:18:54.980 --> 01:18:58.970 align:middle line:84%
One remark contains the
choice of this sign--

01:18:58.970 --> 01:19:01.880 align:middle line:84%
why initial momentum
corresponding to negative root

01:19:01.880 --> 01:19:04.790 align:middle line:84%
and why this corresponding
to positive root,

01:19:04.790 --> 01:19:12.980 align:middle line:84%
and a lot of remarks
related to this factor of Z.

01:19:12.980 --> 01:19:17.150 align:middle line:84%
We will talk about them at
the beginning of next lecture.

01:19:17.150 --> 01:19:20.060 align:middle line:84%
And then after that,
then we are done

01:19:20.060 --> 01:19:23.700 align:middle line:84%
with the general formulation
of interacting theory.

01:19:23.700 --> 01:19:28.310 align:middle line:84%
And now we will be
equipped with the power.

01:19:28.310 --> 01:19:31.520 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, you can calculate
any interacting theory,

01:19:31.520 --> 01:19:36.080 align:middle line:84%
any amplitude, using
perturbation theory.

01:19:36.080 --> 01:19:39.380 align:middle line:84%
But in order to calculate
anything useful,

01:19:39.380 --> 01:19:42.560 align:middle line:84%
we still have to first
learn how to treat fermions,

01:19:42.560 --> 01:19:46.950 align:middle line:84%
how to treat photons, and then
that's what we will do next.

01:19:46.950 --> 01:19:51.030 align:middle line:84%
So we will, starting
next lecture,

01:19:51.030 --> 01:19:54.810 align:middle line:84%
talk about how to
deal with fermions,

01:19:54.810 --> 01:19:57.780 align:middle line:84%
how to introduce fermions, and
after that we'll talk about how

01:19:57.780 --> 01:20:00.930 align:middle line:84%
to introduce photons, and
then we can talk about QED,

01:20:00.930 --> 01:20:04.700 align:middle line:84%
how photons interact with
electrons, et cetera.

01:20:04.700 --> 01:20:06.850 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

01:20:06.850 --> 01:20:10.000 align:middle line:90%